<article>
    <h1>Strict phys&#xAD;i&#xAD;cal dis&#xAD;tanc&#xAD;ing mea&#xAD;sures ahead of re&#xAD;open&#xAD;ing of sports fa&#xAD;cil&#xAD;i&#xAD;ties</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200917/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-17"><time>2020-09-17</time></a>
        - <span>CLASSIFIED&#xAD;S</span>
        - <span role="byline">By JUSTIN CHUA</span>
    </section>

    <p>Phase 2 of Sin­ga­pore’s grad­ual re­open­ing means that many of us can now use the fa­cil­i­ties we re­lied on for our fit­ness fix. Venues such as sta­di­ums, swim­ming com­plexes, sports halls, hard courts, gyms, fit­ness stu­dios, golf cour­ses and bowl­ing cen­tres, in­clud­ing those in con­do­mini­ums, golf and coun­try clubs are among the fa­cil­i­ties that have been al­lowed to re­ceive the pub­lic once more.</p>
    <p>With this, they will have to fol­low strict mea­sures an­nounced by na­tional sports agency Sport Sin­ga­pore (SportSG). They are:</p>
    <p>• The op­er­at­ing ca­pac­ity of these fa­cil­i­ties is re­stricted to 10 sq m per per­son, or a max­i­mum of 50 peo­ple per fa­cil­ity.</p>
    <p>• A dis­tance of 2 me­tres should be kept be­tween in­di­vid­u­als en­gaged in ex­er­cise and sports, with those in­volved in high in­ten­sity or high move­ment ex­er­cises in­doors re­quired to be 3m apart.</p>
    <p>• Group ac­tiv­i­ties are limited to no more than five par­tic­i­pants.</p>
    <p>• If there is more than one group shar­ing a space, the groups should not in­ter­act with each other and must be 3m apart.</p>
    <p>• Shar­ing of equip­ment such as weights and bas­ket­balls should be avoided where pos­si­ble. Strict phys­i­cal dis­tanc­ing mea­sures ahead of re­open­ing of sports fa­cil­i­ties.</p>


</article>

